-- 2022 USAMO Problems/Problem 3
-- Source: AoPS Wiki
-- URL: https://artofproblemsolving.com/wiki/index.php?title=2022_USAMO_Problems/Problem_3

-- Problem (LaTeX):
/-
Let $\mathbb{R}_{>0}$ be the set of all positive real numbers. Find all functions $f:\mathbb{R}_{>0} \to \mathbb{R}_{>0}$ such that for all $x,y\in \mathbb{R}_{>0}$ we have \[f(x) = f(f(f(x)) + y) + f(xf(y)) f(x+y).\]
-/

-- Solution/Answer (LaTeX):
/-
Denote the $n$ th iteration of the function $f(x)$ as $f^{(n)}(x)$ . First we prove that, for any $x$ , $y>0$ such that $f(x)\leq f(y)$ , we have $f^{(2)}(x)\geq y$ . (1) Otherwise, $y>f^{(2)}(x)$ , so $y-f^{(2)}(x)>0$ ; we call this value $c$ , and since $c>0$ , we can substitute $y$ with $c$ in the equation given in the problem, which gives \[f(x)=f(f(f(x))+c)+f(xf(c))f(x+c)\] Recall that $c=y-f^{(2)}(x)$ , which means $f(f(x))+c=y$ ; so $f(x)=f(y)+f(xf(c))f(x+c)$ . However, since $f(x)$ is defined on $\mathbb{R}_{>0} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{>0}$ , we know $f(xf(c))>0$ , $f(x+c)>0$ ; so that $f(xf(c))f(x+c)>0$ , and $f(x)=f(y)+f(xf(c))f(x+c)>f(y)$ , which is a contradiction. Now, since $f(x)\leq f(x)$ , we know $f^{(2)}(x)\geq x$ . Therefore, $f^{(4)}(x)=f^{(2)}(f^{(2)}(x))\geq f^{(2)}(x)$ . Also, we know $f^{(3)}(x)=f^{(2)}(f(x))\geq f(x)$ , and hence $f^{(5)}(x)=f^{(2)}(f^{(3)}(x)) \geq f^{(3)}(x)$ . This means $f(x)\leq f^{(5)}(x)$ , which is $f(x)\leq f(f^{(4)}(x))$ ; from (1) we know $f^{(2)}(x)\geq f^{(4)}(x)$ . Since $f^{(2)}(x)\geq f^{(4)}(x)$ , while we also obtained $f^{(4)}(x)\geq f^{(2)}(x)$ , we know $f^{(2)}(x)=f^{(4)}(x)$ . Then we try to prove that $f(x)$ is injective. If $f(x)$ is not injective, this means there exists some $a<b$ such that $f(a)=f(b)$ . First consider substituting $x$ with $f^{(2)}(x)$ and $y$ with $a$ , hence we obtain \[f(f^{(2)}(x))=f(f(f(f^{(2)}(x)))+a)+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(a))f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)\] which means $f^{(3)}(x)=f(f^{(4)}(x)+a)+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(a))f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(a))f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)$ , and that obtains $f^{(3)}(x)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)(1+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(a)))$ . Symmetrically, if we substitute $x$ with $f^{(2)}(x)$ and $y$ with $b$ , we shall obtain $f^{(3)}(x)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+b)(1+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(b)))$ , so that \[f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)(1+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(a)))=f(f^{(2)}(x)+b)(1+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(b)))\] However, as $f(a)=f(b)$ , we have $(1+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(a)))=(1+f(f^{(2)}(x)f(b)))$ ; then we know \[f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+b).\] Now we substitute only $y$ with $a$ , to obtain \[f(x)=f(f(f(x))+a)+f(x(f(a))f(x+a)\] which is $f(x)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)+f(x(f(a))f(x+a)$ . Symmetrically substituting only $y$ with $b$ , we get $f(x)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+b)+f(x(f(b))f(x+b)$ , so finally \[f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)+f(x(f(a))f(x+a)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+b)+f(x(f(b))f(x+b)\] But we know $f(f^{(2)}(x)+a)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+b)$ , and as $f(a)=f(b)$ , $f(x(f(a))=f(xf(b))$ , so finally we know $f(x+a)=f(x+b)$ . This means $f(x)$ is a periodic function with $b-a$ as a period. We can always take an arbitrarily large integer $n$ , so that $f^{(2)}(a)<a+n(b-a)$ . Recall the statement of (1), whose contrapositive is "if $f^{(2)}(x)<y$ , we have $f(x)>f(y)$ ". By comparing $f^{(2)}(a)<a+n(b-a)$ , we know $f(a)>f(a+n(b-a))=f(a)$ , which is a contradiction! Hence, we finished the proof that $f(x)$ is injective. Then,as $f^{(4)}(x)=f^{(2)}(f^{(2)}(x))=f^{(2)}(x)$ , we can conclude that $f^{(2)}(x)=x$ . Recall the original equation, which $f(x)=f(f(f(x))+y)+f(xf(y))f(x+y)=f(f^{(2)}(x)+y)+f(xf(y))f(x+y)$ , and it further means \[f(x)=f(x+y)+f(xf(y))f(x+y)\] . Substituting $x$ with $1$ gives $f(1)=f(1+y)+f(1\cdot f(y))f(1+y)=f(1+y)+f(f(y))f(1+y)=f(1+y)+yf(1+y)$ , so $f(1)=f(1+y)(1+y)$ and thus $f(1+y)=\frac{f(1)}{1+y}$ . Denote $f(1)$ as d, so we have proved that for all $z=1+y>1$ , it is true that $f(z)=\frac{d}{z}$ . For $z\leq 1$ , we substitute $y$ with $f(z)$ , which gives $f(x)=f(x+f(z))+f(xf(f(z)))f(x+f(z))=f(x+f(z))+f(xz)f(x+f(z))$ . As the choice for $x$ is arbitrary, we can always take some $x>\frac{1}{z}$ . Since $z\leq 1$ , we know $x>1$ , and $xz>\frac{1}{z}\cdot z=1$ . So for the equation $f(x)=f(x+f(z))+f(xz)f(x+f(z))$ , we have $x>1$ , $x+f(z)>x>1$ , and $xz>1$ . Then we can write \[\frac{d}{x}=\frac{d}{x+f(z)}+\frac{d}{xz}\cdot\frac{d}{x+f(z)}\] Multiplying $\frac{xz(x+f(z))}{d}$ on both sides give $z(x+f(z))=xz+d$ , so $f(z)=\frac{d}{z}$ . We have finally proved that, for all $z$ , it is true that $f(z)=\frac{d}{z}$ ; and we thus conclude our final answer, that \[\boxed{f(x)=\frac{d}{x}}\] where $d\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}$ . ~ć•°äą‹č°ś
-/

